Right. You want to know about the territories the [Kingdom of England](/Kingdom_of_England) once held. Don't expect a rosy narrative; history, like most things, is a messy affair.

"English Empire" redirects here. For post-1707 possessions, see [British Empire](/British_Empire). For Plantagenet territories, see [Angevin Empire](/Angevin_Empire).

Let's be clear: the English overseas possessions, sometimes referred to rather grandly as the "English Empire," were a collection of lands acquired by the [Kingdom of England](/Kingdom_of_England) before 1707. That was the year the [Acts of Union](/Acts_of_Union_1707) decided to merge England with Scotland, creating the [Kingdom of Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain). After that, it all became a much larger, and arguably more complicated, affair – the [British Empire](/British_Empire).

The earliest ventures, naturally, were closer to home. [Ireland](/Ireland) was the first to feel the English boot, a persistent thorn in the side that would continue to fester for centuries. Then came the age of exploration, spurred by monarchs like [Henry VII of England](/Henry_VII_of_England) and his granddaughter, [Elizabeth I](/Elizabeth_I_of_England). But it wasn't until [James VI](/James_VI_and_I) of Scotland inherited the English throne in 1603, ruling as James I, that permanent overseas settlements truly began to take root.

[North America](/North_America) became a prime target. [Jamestown, Virginia](/Jamestown,_Virginia), established in 1607, was one of the first, despite being in territory already claimed by the Spanish. The [West Indies](/West_Indies) followed, and in Asia, the English established "[factories](/Factory_(trading_post))" – essentially trading posts – in the [East Indies](/East_Indies), such as [Bantam](/Bantam_(city)), and later in the [Indian subcontinent](/Indian_subcontinent), starting with [Surat](/Surat). The construction of [Fort St George](/Fort_St._George_(India)) on the Indian coast in 1639 marked a more fortified presence. Even marriage alliances played a role; in 1661, [King Charles II](/Charles_II_of_England)'s union with [Catherine of Braganza](/Catherine_of_Braganza) brought [Tangier](/English_Tangier) in [North Africa](/North_Africa) and [Bombay](/Mumbai) in India into English hands as part of her [dowry](/Dowry).

In North America, [Newfoundland](/Newfoundland_Colony) and [Virginia](/Virginia_Colony) were the initial hubs. The 17th century saw a flurry of activity: [Maine](/Province_of_Maine), [Plymouth](/Plymouth_Colony), [New Hampshire](/Province_of_New_Hampshire), [Salem, Massachusetts](/Salem,_Massachusetts), [Massachusetts Bay](/Massachusetts_Bay_Colony), [Nova Scotia](/Nova_Scotia), [Connecticut](/Connecticut_Colony), [New Haven](/New_Haven_Colony), [Maryland](/Province_of_Maryland), and [Rhode Island and Providence](/Rhode_Island_Colony) were all established. The English weren't shy about taking what they wanted, either. In 1664, they seized [New Netherland](/New_Netherland) and [New Sweden](/New_Sweden) from the Dutch, re-christening them [New York](/Province_of_New_York) and [New Jersey](/Province_of_New_Jersey), and absorbing parts of what would become [Delaware](/Delaware) and [Pennsylvania](/Pennsylvania).

### Origins

A replica of [Cabot](/John_Cabot)'s ship the [Matthew](/Matthew_(1497_ship))

The [Kingdom of England](/Kingdom_of_England), as a distinct entity, really solidifies its identity with [Æthelstan](/%C3%86thelstan) in 927. Before that, it was a different sort of patchwork. During the [House of Knýtlinga](/House_of_Kn%C3%BDtlinga)'s rule (1013-1042), England was part of a larger, more fluid [personal union](/Personal_union) that stretched into [Scandinavia](/Scandinavia). Then came the [Norman conquest of England](/Norman_conquest_of_England) in 1066. [William the Conqueror](/William_the_Conqueror), [Duke of Normandy](/Duke_of_Normandy), brought his own continental ambitions with him, making the Duchy a [Crown land](/Crown_land) of the English throne. For centuries, English kings held significant territories in [France](/France) due to this connection. The [Angevin Empire](/Angevin_Empire), under the [Plantagenet](/Plantagenet) dynasty, was a vast collection of lands across the [British Isles](/British_Isles) and France. This continental entanglement, however, inevitably led to conflict. The [Hundred Years' War](/Hundred_Years%27_War) (1337-1453) saw England fight to maintain its French holdings. By the war's end, only the [Pale of Calais](/Pale_of_Calais) remained, and even that was lost in 1558. The [Channel Islands](/Channel_Islands), however, still cling to their historical ties to the English Crown, a persistent echo of those continental ambitions.

### Ireland

The expansion into [Ireland](/Ireland) began early, around 1169, with the [Norman invasion of Ireland](/Norman_invasion_of_Ireland). Thousands of English and Welsh settlers followed, establishing English dominion. [Friedrich Engels](/Friedrich_Engels) famously called Ireland the "first English colony." For centuries, the English monarch claimed the [Lordship of Ireland](/Lordship_of_Ireland), but actual control was often confined to a region known as [The Pale](/The_Pale). Much of [Munster](/Munster), [Ulster](/Ulster), and [Connaught](/Connaught) remained outside English authority until the Tudors and Stuarts decided to assert more direct control. The Tudor monarchs initiated the [plantations of Ireland](/Plantations_of_Ireland) in the 16th century, settling Protestant colonists, particularly in King's and Queen's Counties (now [County Offaly](/County_Offaly) and [County Laois](/County_Laois)) in 1556. A joint-stock plantation was attempted near [Cork city](/Cork_city) in the late 1560s. The 17th century saw the significant [Plantation of Ulster](/Plantation_of_Ulster), bringing thousands of Scottish and English settlers to that province. English authority in Ireland was a long, drawn-out struggle, only fully consolidated when Ireland was incorporated into the [United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland](/United_Kingdom_of_Great_Britain_and_Ireland) in 1801.

### New World Beginnings

The age of discovery, kicked off by [Christopher Columbus](/Christopher_Columbus)'s westward voyages in 1492, was a catalyst. He landed in the [West Indies](/West_Indies), mistaking them for Asia and deeming the indigenous peoples "Indians." The Spanish, driven by a lust for riches, found gold but also a vast population to exploit. The [Portuguese](/Portuguese_Empire) and [Spanish](/Spanish_Empire) success spurred [King Henry VII of England](/Henry_VII_of_England) to commission [John Cabot](/John_Cabot) in 1497 to find a westward route to [Asia](/Asia) – the elusive [North West Passage](/North_West_Passage). Cabot reached [Newfoundland](/Newfoundland_(island)), believing he'd found Asia, but made no attempt at settlement. His subsequent voyage in 1498 vanished.

Meanwhile, Spain was busy carving up the Americas. The [Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire](/Spanish_conquest_of_the_Aztec_Empire) (1529-21) by [Hernán Cortés](/Hern%C3%A1n_Cort%C3%A9s) and the [Spanish conquest of the Inca Empire](/Spanish_conquest_of_the_Inca_Empire) revealed the immense wealth and complex societies of the New World, transforming Europe's understanding and Spain into a global power, especially after the discovery of vast silver deposits.

England, having broken with Catholic Spain through the [English Reformation](/English_Reformation), found itself in conflict. [Elizabeth I](/Elizabeth_I_of_England) sanctioned [privateers](/Privateer) like [Hawkins](/John_Hawkins_(naval_commander)) and [Drake](/Francis_Drake) to harass Spanish shipping in [West Africa](/West_Africa) and the Americas. Writers like [Richard Hakluyt](/Richard_Hakluyt) and [John Dee](/John_Dee) began advocating for England to establish its own overseas empire, a daunting task with Spain already dominant in the Americas and [Portugal](/Portugal) holding sway in Africa and Asia. The [French](/French_colonization_of_the_Americas) were also making inroads in [North America](/North_America), settling the [Saint Lawrence River](/Saint_Lawrence_River).

### The First English Overseas Colonies

The initial wave of English overseas colonization, ironically, started not in the Americas, but in [Ireland](/Ireland) with the [plantations of Ireland](/Plantations_of_Ireland) following the [Tudor conquest of Ireland](/Tudor_conquest_of_Ireland). A specific joint-stock colony was established in the late 1560s near [Cork city](/Cork_city). Many involved in these Irish ventures later turned their attention to North America, particularly a group known as the [West Country men](/West_Country_men).

The first attempts at permanent English settlements in [North America](/North_America) occurred in the last quarter of the 16th century, during [Queen Elizabeth](/Elizabeth_I_of_England)'s reign. This was a generation before the [Plantation of Ulster](/Plantation_of_Ulster) and shortly after the Munster plantations. Driven by a desire for land, trade, and religious freedom, English colonial activity surged. In the 17th century, the [West Indies](/West_Indies) actually attracted more English emigrants than North America.

[Queen Elizabeth](/Elizabeth_I_of_England)

### Early Claims

The quest for the [North West Passage](/North_West_Passage) led [Martin Frobisher](/Martin_Frobisher) on voyages starting in 1576. He landed on [Baffin Island](/Baffin_Island), conducting the first recorded [Church of England](/Church_of_England) service on North American soil. He claimed territory on behalf of Queen Elizabeth, even reaching [Greenland](/Greenland) and claiming it for England in 1578.

Concurrently, between 1577 and 1580, [Sir Francis Drake](/Francis_Drake) was [circumnavigating the globe](/Circumnavigation). He claimed [Elizabeth Island](/Elizabeth_Island_(Cape_Horn)) off [Cape Horn](/Cape_Horn) and another Elizabeth Island in the [Straits of Magellan](/Straits_of_Magellan) for his queen. In 1579, he claimed a vast swathe of [California](/California) as "[New Albion](/New_Albion)". These were ambitious claims, but they remained just that – claims, without any follow-up settlements.

In 1578, [Humphrey Gilbert](/Humphrey_Gilbert), Drake's half-brother, received a patent for overseas exploration. His initial attempt to reach the West Indies and establish a colony failed. In 1583, he sailed to [Newfoundland](/Newfoundland_(island)), formally taking possession of [St John's](/St._John%27s,_Newfoundland_and_Labrador) and surrounding lands, though he left no settlers. He did not survive the return voyage.

### The First Overseas Settlements

On March 25, 1584, [Sir Walter Raleigh](/Walter_Raleigh) was granted a charter by [Queen Elizabeth I](/Elizabeth_I_of_England) to colonize an area of [North America](/North_America) named [Virginia](/Virginia_Colony) in her honour. This charter stipulated a seven-year deadline for settlement. Raleigh and Elizabeth envisioned the venture as a source of New World riches and a base for privateering against [Spain](/Spain). Raleigh himself never set foot in North America, though he did lead expeditions to [South America](/South_America) in search of the mythical city of [El Dorado](/El_Dorado). Instead, he dispatched others to found the ill-fated [Roanoke Colony](/Roanoke_Colony), forever known as the "Lost Colony."

On December 31, 1600, [Elizabeth I](/Elizabeth_I_of_England) granted a charter to the [East India Company](/East_India_Company), officially known as "The Governor and Company of Merchants of London Trading into the East Indies." This company established its first trading post in the [East Indies](/East_Indies) at [Bantam](/Banten_(town)) on [Java](/Java), followed by others, beginning with [Surat](/Surat), on the coasts of what are now [India](/India) and [Bangladesh](/Bangladesh).

Most of the early English colonies in North America and the [West Indies](/West_Indies) were [proprietary](/Proprietary_colony) colonies. These were governed by [Proprietors](/Proprietary_Governor) appointed under [Royal charters](/Royal_charter) granted to individuals or [joint stock companies](/Joint_stock_company). Notable early examples include the [Virginia Company](/London_Company), which established the successful settlements at [Jamestown](/Jamestown,_Virginia) in 1607 and [Bermuda](/Bermuda) (unofficially in 1609, officially in 1612, with its administration later transferred to the [Somers Isles Company](/Somers_Isles_Company)). The [Newfoundland Company](/London_and_Bristol_Company) also settled [Cuper's Cove](/Cuper%27s_Cove) near [St John's, Newfoundland](/St._John%27s,_Newfoundland_and_Labrador) in 1610. Colonies like Rhode Island, Connecticut, and Massachusetts Bay were [charter colonies](/Charter_colony), established through [land patents](/Land_patent) from the Crown. Some charters even extended claims westward to the [Pacific Ocean](/Pacific_Ocean), based on [Francis Drake](/Francis_Drake)'s explorations, a provision found in the charters for Connecticut, Massachusetts Bay, and Virginia.

[Bermuda](/Bermuda), still a [British Overseas Territory](/British_Overseas_Territory), owes its settlement to the wreck of the Virginia Company's flagship, the [Sea Venture](/Sea_Venture), in 1609. The town of [St George's](/St._George%27s,_Bermuda), founded in 1612, is considered the oldest continuously inhabited English settlement in the New World. Bermuda played a significant role in the development of English and British empires, contributing to maritime commerce, continental and West Indian settlement, and naval power through its privateers.

Between 1640 and 1660, the [West Indies](/West_Indies) were the primary destination for English emigrants, receiving over two-thirds of those heading to the New World. By 1650, the Caribbean held 44,000 English settlers, significantly more than the 12,000 on the [Chesapeake](/Chesapeake_Bay) or the 23,000 in [New England](/New_England). [Barbados](/Barbados) was the most substantial English settlement during this period.

In 1660, [King Charles II](/Charles_II_of_England) established the [Royal African Company](/Royal_African_Company), a venture deeply involved in the [Atlantic slave trade](/Atlantic_slave_trade), headed by his brother, [James, Duke of York](/James_II_of_England). As mentioned, Charles II's marriage to [Catherine of Braganza](/Catherine_of_Braganza) brought him Tangier and Bombay. Tangier, however, proved too costly and was abandoned in 1684.

Following the English seizure of [Fort Amsterdam](/Fort_Amsterdam) from the Dutch in 1664, England took control of [New Netherland](/New_Netherland), including [New Amsterdam](/New_Amsterdam). This acquisition, formalized in 1667, contributed to the [Second Anglo–Dutch War](/Second_Anglo%E2%80%93Dutch_War). New Netherland was renamed the [Province of New York](/Province_of_New_York). The English also gained control of the former [New Sweden](/New_Sweden), which had become a Dutch possession and was later incorporated into [Pennsylvania](/Pennsylvania). Although the Dutch briefly recaptured New Netherland in 1673, they ceded it permanently under the [Treaty of Westminster](/Treaty_of_Westminster_(1674)) in 1674.

### Council of Trade and Foreign Plantations

• Main article: [Board of Trade](/Board_of_Trade)

In 1621, facing economic difficulties due to a decline in overseas trade, [King James I](/James_I_of_England) instructed his [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_England) to form a committee to investigate the causes. This ad hoc group, known as "The Lords of the Committee of the Privy Council appointed for the consideration of all matters relating to Trade and Foreign Plantations," eventually evolved into the [Board of Trade](/Board_of_Trade), which has operated with few interruptions since its inception. This committee quickly became involved in promoting profitable enterprises in English possessions, particularly the production of [tobacco](/Tobacco) and [sugar](/Sugar).

### The Americas

#### List of English possessions in North America

[Captain John Smith](/John_Smith_(explorer)), "Admiral of New England"

*   [St John's, Newfoundland](/St._John%27s,_Newfoundland_and_Labrador): Chartered in 1583 by [Sir Humphrey Gilbert](/Humphrey_Gilbert), seasonal settlement existed from around 1520, with permanent residents by 1620.
*   [Roanoke Colony](/Roanoke_Colony): Located in present-day [North Carolina](/North_Carolina). First established in 1585, abandoned the following year. A second attempt in 1587 resulted in the disappearance of the colonists, giving rise to the "Lost Colony" moniker. [Virginia Dare](/Virginia_Dare) was among the lost.
*   [Cuttyhunk](/Cuttyhunk): One of the [Elizabeth Islands](/Elizabeth_Islands) in present-day [Massachusetts](/Massachusetts). [Bartholomew Gosnold](/Bartholomew_Gosnold) established a small fort and trading post here in 1602, but it was abandoned after only a month.
*   The [Virginia Company](/Virginia_Company): Chartered in 1606. In 1624, its territories became the [royal](/Crown_colony) [Colony of Virginia](/Colony_of_Virginia).
*   [Jamestown, Virginia](/Jamestown,_Virginia): Founded by the [Virginia Company of London](/London_Company) in 1607.
*   [Bermuda](/Bermuda): Also known as the Somers Isles, situated in the [North Atlantic](/North_Atlantic). Accidentally settled by the [Virginia Company of London](/Virginia_Company_of_London) in 1609 after the shipwreck of their flagship, the [Sea Venture](/Sea_Venture). Possession was formalized in 1612 with the establishment of [St George's](/St._George%27s,_Bermuda), the oldest continuously inhabited English town in the New World. Administration passed to the [Somers Isles Company](/Somers_Isles_Company) in 1615. The [House of Assembly of Bermuda](/House_of_Assembly_of_Bermuda) was established in 1620. Complaints from Bermudians led to the revocation of the company's charter in 1684.
*   [Henricus](/Henricus): Also known as Henricopolis or Henrico Town. Founded by the London Virginia Company in 1611 as an alternative to Jamestown, but it was largely destroyed during the [Indian massacre of 1622](/Indian_massacre_of_1622).
*   [Popham Colony](/Popham_Colony): Established on August 13, 1607, by the [Virginia Company of Plymouth](/Plymouth_Company) along the [Kennebec River](/Kennebec_River) in present-day [Maine](/Maine). The company held a license to settle between the [38th parallel](/38th_parallel_north) and the [45th parallel](/45th_parallel_north). However, Popham was abandoned after about a year, and the company became inactive.

Plaque at [St John's](/St._John%27s,_Newfoundland_and_Labrador) marking [Humphrey Gilbert](/Humphrey_Gilbert)'s landing there, 1583.

*   The [Society of Merchant Venturers](/Society_of_Merchant_Venturers) of [Bristol](/Bristol) began settling [Newfoundland](/Newfoundland_and_Labrador):
    *   [Cuper's Cove](/Cuper%27s_Cove): Founded in 1610, abandoned in the 1620s.
    *   [Bristol's Hope](/Subdivision_1I,_Newfoundland_and_Labrador): Founded in 1618, abandoned in the 1630s.
*   The [London and Bristol Company](/London_and_Bristol_Company) also established a presence in [Newfoundland](/Newfoundland_and_Labrador).
    *   [Cambriol](/Cambriol): Founded in 1617 by [Sir William Vaughan](/William_Vaughan_(writer)) on land purchased from the [Newfoundland Company](/Newfoundland_Company). The colony was abandoned by 1637.
    *   [Renews](/Renews,_Newfoundland_and_Labrador): Founded in 1615, abandoned in 1619.
*   [Plymouth Council for New England](/Plymouth_Council_for_New_England):
    *   [Plymouth Colony](/Plymouth_Colony): Founded in 1620, merged with [Massachusetts Bay Colony](/Massachusetts_Bay_Colony) in 1691.
    *   [Ferryland, Newfoundland](/Ferryland,_Newfoundland_and_Labrador): Granted to [George Calvert, 1st Baron Baltimore](/George_Calvert,_1st_Baron_Baltimore) in 1620, with settlers arriving in August 1621.
    *   [Province of Maine](/Province_of_Maine): Granted in 1622, sold to [Massachusetts Bay Colony](/Massachusetts_Bay_Colony) in 1677.
    *   [South Falkland, Newfoundland](/South_Falkland): Founded in 1623 by [Henry Cary, 1st Viscount Falkland](/Henry_Cary,_1st_Viscount_Falkland).
    *   [Province of New Hampshire](/Province_of_New_Hampshire): Settled in 1623, later becoming [New Hampshire](/New_Hampshire). See also [New Hampshire Grants](/New_Hampshire_Grants).
    *   [Cape Ann](/Gloucester,_Massachusetts): An unsuccessful fishing colony established in 1624 by the [Dorchester Company](/Dorchester_Company).
    *   [Salem Colony](/Salem,_Massachusetts): Settled in 1628, merged with the Massachusetts Bay Colony the following year.
    *   [Massachusetts Bay Colony](/Massachusetts_Bay_Colony): Founded in 1629, later becoming part of Massachusetts.
    *   [Providence Island colony](/Providence_Island_colony): Established in 1630 by English [Puritans](/Puritan) on [Providence Island](/Providencia_Island,_Colombia), in the [Bay of Moskitia](/Bay_of_Moskitia). Controlled by the [Providence Island Company](/Providence_Island_Company), it served as a base for privateering against Spanish interests. Captured by the Spanish in 1641.
    *   [Nova Scotia](/Nova_Scotia): Under English control from 1654 to 1670.
    *   [Connecticut Colony](/Connecticut_Colony): Founded in 1633, later becoming part of [Connecticut](/Connecticut).
    *   [Province of Maryland](/Province_of_Maryland): Founded in 1634, later becoming [Maryland](/Maryland).
    *   [Province of New Albion](/Province_of_New_Albion): Chartered in 1634, but had failed by 1649–1650.
    *   [Saybrook Colony](/Saybrook_Colony): Founded in 1635, merged with Connecticut in 1644.
    *   [Rhode Island and Providence Plantations](/Rhode_Island_Colony): First settled in 1636.
    *   [New Haven Colony](/New_Haven_Colony): Founded in 1638, merged with Connecticut in 1665.
    *   [Gardiners Island](/Gardiners_Island): Founded in 1639, now part of [East Hampton, New York](/East_Hampton_(town),_New_York).
    *   The [New England Confederation](/New_England_Confederation): Officially the 'United Colonies of New England', formed in 1643 as a military alliance between Massachusetts Bay, Plymouth, Connecticut, and New Haven. Its aim was to unite the [Puritan](/Puritan) colonies against [Native Americans](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States). It also included provisions for the return of fugitive criminals and [indentured servants](/Indentured_servant).
    *   [Province of New York](/Province_of_New_York): Captured from the Dutch in 1664.
    *   [Province of New Jersey](/Province_of_New_Jersey): Also captured in 1664. It was later divided into [West Jersey](/West_Jersey) and [East Jersey](/East_Jersey) after 1674.
    *   [Rupert's Land](/Rupert%27s_Land): Named after [Prince Rupert of the Rhine](/Prince_Rupert_of_the_Rhine). In 1668, expeditions were sent to explore trade routes into [Hudson Bay](/Hudson_Bay). [Fort Rupert](/Waskaganish,_Quebec) was founded at the mouth of the [Rupert River](/Rupert_River). Prince Rupert became the first governor of the [Hudson's Bay Company](/Hudson%27s_Bay_Company), established in 1670.
    *   [Province of Pennsylvania](/Province_of_Pennsylvania): Founded in 1681, though initially settled by Dutch and Swedes.
    *   [Delaware Colony](/Delaware_Colony): Separated from Pennsylvania in 1704.
    *   [Province of Carolina](/Province_of_Carolina): Settled in 1653 at the [Albemarle Settlements](/Albemarle_Settlements). Chartered in 1663 as a single territory, it effectively functioned as two separate colonies:
        *   [Province of North Carolina](/Province_of_North_Carolina): Permanently settled from 1653, becoming a separate British colony in 1710.
        *   [Province of South Carolina](/Province_of_South_Carolina): Permanently settled from 1670, becoming a separate British colony in 1710.
    *   One possession established after 1707 as a [British colony](/British_colony):
        *   [Province of Georgia](/Province_of_Georgia): First settled in 1733.

#### List of English possessions in the West Indies

*   [Barbados](/Barbados): First visited by an English ship in 1605, settlement began in 1625. It quickly became a major English settlement in the Americas.
*   [Saint Kitts](/Saint_Kitts): Settled by the English in 1623, followed by the French. The indigenous [Kalinago](/Kalinago) were massacred, and the island partitioned. It frequently changed hands between English and French control before becoming permanently British in 1783.
*   [Nevis](/Nevis): Settled in 1628.
*   [Providence Island colony](/Providence_Island_colony): Settled by the [Providence Island Company](/Providence_Island_Company) in 1629 and captured by Spain in 1641.
*   [Montserrat](/Montserrat): Settled in 1632.
*   [Antigua](/Antigua): Settled in 1632 by English colonists from Saint Kitts.
*   [The Bahamas](/The_Bahamas): Largely deserted until 1648 when the [Eleutheran Adventurers](/Eleutheran_Adventurers) settled on [Eleuthera](/Eleuthera).
*   [Anguilla](/Anguilla): First colonized by English settlers from St Kitts in 1650. Briefly held by the French before being returned to England in 1667.
*   [Jamaica](/Jamaica): Conquered from the Spanish in 1655.
*   [Barbuda](/Barbuda): Colonized by the English in 1666.
*   [The Cayman Islands](/Cayman_Islands): Visited by [Sir Francis Drake](/Francis_Drake) in 1586. Informally settled by pirates and others in the 17th century. England gained control with Jamaica in 1670.

#### List of English claims in Central and South America

*   [Elizabeth Island](/Elizabeth_Island_(Cape_Horn)): Claimed by Sir Francis Drake in 1578, but no settlements were made and the exact location is uncertain.
*   [Guiana](/British_Guiana): An attempt to establish a colony in 1604 failed to find [gold](/Gold) and lasted only two years.
*   [Mosquito Coast](/Mosquito_Coast): A small part was occupied by the [Providence Island Company](/Providence_Island_Company) in the 17th century.
*   [Falkland Islands](/Falkland_Islands): Claimed by mariner [John Strong](/John_Strong_(mariner)) in 1690.

#### English possessions in India and the East Indies

[Fort St George](/Fort_St._George,_India), [Madras](/Chennai), the first English fortress in India.

*   [Bantam](/Bantam_(city)): The [East India Company](/East_India_Company) established a permanent "[factory](/Factory_(trading_post))" here in 1602.
*   [Surat](/Surat): The East India Company settled here in 1608. It was the company's first headquarters, but the command centre was moved to [Bombay](/Bombay) in 1687.
*   [Machilipatnam](/Machilipatnam): A trading factory was established on the [Coromandel Coast](/Coromandel_Coast) in 1611.
*   [Run](/Run_(island)): A spice island. [Nathaniel Courthope](/Nathaniel_Courthope) defended it against the [Dutch East India Company](/Dutch_East_India_Company) starting in 1616. After Courthope's death in 1620, the English left. The [Treaty of Westminster](/Treaty_of_Westminster_(1654)) was supposed to return Run to England, but it wasn't. Following the [Second Anglo-Dutch War](/Second_Anglo-Dutch_War), England kept [Manhattan](/Manhattan) while formally abandoning Run to the Dutch.
*   [Fort St George](/Fort_St._George_(India)): Founded in 1639 at Madras ([Chennai](/Chennai)).
*   [Bombay](/Mumbai): Transferred to England in 1661 as part of the dowry of [Catherine of Braganza](/Catherine_of_Braganza). Leased to the [East India Company](/East_India_Company) in 1668. Its population grew significantly, and it became the headquarters of the [Bombay Presidency](/Bombay_Presidency).
*   [Bencoolen](/British_Bencoolen): An East India Company pepper-trading centre on [Sumatra](/Sumatra), established in 1685.
*   [Calcutta](/Kolkata): Settled by the East India Company in 1690.

#### English possessions in Africa

English Tangier, 1670. [James Island](/Kunta_Kinteh_Island) and [Fort Gambia](/Fort_Gambia).

*   [The Gambia River](/Gambia_River): In 1588, exclusive trade rights were sold to English merchants. In 1618, a charter was granted for trade with [the Gambia](/The_Gambia) and the [Gold Coast](/Gold_Coast_(British_colony)). The English captured [Fort Gambia](/Fort_Gambia) from the Dutch in 1661. The fort and island were renamed Fort James and James Island, respectively, after [James, Duke of York](/James_II_of_England). The territory traded in [gold](/Gold), [ivory](/Ivory), and [slaves](/Slave).
*   [English Tangier](/English_Tangier): Acquired in 1661 as part of [Catherine of Braganza](/Catherine_of_Braganza)'s dowry. Abandoned in 1684 due to the high cost of its upkeep.
*   [Saint Helena](/Saint_Helena): Settled by the English [East India Company](/East_India_Company) in 1659.

### English possessions in Europe

*   [Duchy of Normandy](/Duchy_of_Normandy): Associated with the English crown from 1066. Lost to [Philip II of France](/Philip_II_of_France) in 1204. The [Channel Islands](/Channel_Islands) remained linked.
*   [County of Anjou](/County_of_Anjou) and [County of Maine](/County_of_Maine): Merged with the English crown in 1154. Lost to France in 1204.
*   [Duchy of Aquitaine](/Duchy_of_Aquitaine): Passed to the English through the marriage of [Eleanor of Aquitaine](/Eleanor_of_Aquitaine) in 1152. Lost to France by 1453 after the [Hundred Years' War](/Hundred_Years%27_War).
*   [Kingdom of France](/Kingdom_of_France): [Edward III of England](/Edward_III_of_England) claimed the French throne in 1340. [Henry V of England](/Henry_V_of_England) was recognized as heir by the [Treaty of Troyes](/Treaty_of_Troyes) in 1420. English claims were finally abandoned by the [Treaty of Picquigny](/Treaty_of_Picquigny) in 1475. English monarchs continued to use the title King/Queen of France until 1801.
*   [Pale of Calais](/Pale_of_Calais): Captured in 1347. Recaptured by the French in 1558.
*   [Tournai](/Tournai): Occupied by [Henry VIII of England](/Henry_VIII_of_England) in 1513. Returned to France in 1519.
*   [Le Havre](/Le_Havre): Occupied by English troops in 1562. Reconquered by the French the following year.
*   [Cautionary Towns](/Cautionary_Towns): English possession of [Flushing](/Vlissingen) and [Brill](/Brielle) confirmed in 1585. Sold to the Dutch Republic in 1616.
*   [Dunkirk](/Dunkirk): Captured from the Spanish in 1658 and granted to England. Sold back to France in 1662.
*   [Gibraltar](/Gibraltar): Captured in 1704. Ceded to [Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain) in 1713.

### Transformation into British Empire

The [Treaty of Union of 1706](/Acts_of_Union_1707), effective from 1707, merged England and Scotland into [Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain). This meant that English companies and colonies effectively became [British colonies](/Evolution_of_the_British_Empire).

